fering and monetary expenditures is staggering.  Worldwide $895 billion a year is currently being spent on combating cancer.  Americans suffering from cancer spend $200 billion per year for treatment_ and cancer treatment costs continue to rise and grow the cancer industry.      The largest medical care cost associated with cancer results from hospitalizations.  Annually there are 1.2 million hospital admissions in the U.S. just for cancer treatment.  Effective treatment methods resulting in fewer days of hospital care are desperately needed.  Primary treatment methods currently used in cancer care include surgery_ radiation therapy_ chemotherapy_ drug therapy_ hormone therapy_ and other scientific tactics such as bone marrow replacement_ biological response modifiers_ gene therapy_ and diet.  It is well known that these methods can or may cause sickness_ pain_ disfigurement_ depression_ baldness_ and the spread of the cancer as well as being vastly and devastatingly ineffective.  The price of cancer drugs is mind-blowing and the cost varies with the type of cancer treated.  Chemotherapeutic drug treatments start at about $40_000 per year with the newest formulations reaching a $100_000 annually_ and the recent pharmaceutical â€œcuresâ€ that have been announced by researchers start at $93_000; for most people_ drugs and other therapies only buy a few more months of life.  Cancer drugs cost much more than drugs for other illnesses and the co-pays are higher for prescribed cancer drugs than those for any other types of treatment.  http://www.cancercodecorp.com/costs.html','2012-05-13T05:45:20+0000','359461477448185_3483119','b5d78332adadf26df7823f736f21627664b878b0',0,'An issue no doubt. Research costs are high. The average length of time to develop a new drug and bring it to market is ten years. Sometimes this means only those therapies wth mass appeal are of interest to drug companies to ensure return on investment. The main investigator for Gleevec presented last 