me Proud to call you my friend!! ','2014-09-06T07:01:21+0000',1,208352,'2014-10-29 13:17:57'),('198826403502374_231851840217477','dddae424503633477c35cfffc0c80adff57fdf76','Breast Cancer and the Environment â€“ New report from the Institute of Medicine ... http://tinyurl.com/8yk4u4d','2011-12-12T07:34:51+0000','231851840217477_2041087','01f33c59074a13861322e501acf7f934f76481ad',0,'and reducng toxic body burden of harmful chemicals in personal care products. Ava Anderson Non Toxic','2011-12-18T10:19:08+0000',0,208353,'2014-10-29 13:23:22'),('198826403502374_190617877698002','dddae424503633477c35cfffc0c80adff57fdf76','Excellent educational video from Dr. Magda Havas: _Wi-Fi in Schools is Safe. True or False?_ ... http://tinyurl.com/7vdwwgd ','2011-12-10T02:22:38+0000','190617877698002_964457','3ecb53a6e0d956760de6ed3917bdd35afdb719a0',0,'Thank you - interesting','2011-12-10T08:26:01+0000',0,208354,'2014-10-29 13:23:22'),('198826403502374_129175653859205','dddae424503633477c35cfffc0c80adff57fdf76','Action Alert on Pesticides! The B.C. gov_t is conducting an online survey to gauge citizensâ€™ views on a proposed ban on the use of cosmetic pesticides. It only takes a few minutes to fill out the questionnaire. The deadline for submissions is Friday_ December 16_ 2011. We urge everyone_ no matter where you live_ to please register your support! http://tinyurl.com/3gxkruf ','2011-11-24T19:51:27+0000','129175653859205_209524','e66a4983ca74d41961b2ef1b51084a2ad64518a2',0,'I included this long submission in the \'comment\' box: >>There must be immediate regulations to establish a no-spray buffer zone around all homes of people with medical environmental illnesses. 1) Do not attempt to establish a list of restricted pesticides- a much better policy and procedure is to to ban all cosmetic pesticides except the established lists of less-toxic ones that are acceptable in organic agriculture (OMRI and CGSB- see notes at bottom; some of those might also be considered too toxic for cosmetic uses and also banned). Regulations should recognize OMRIâ€™s and CGSBâ€™s three categories of â€œApproved,â€ â€œRestricted,â€ and â€œProhibited.â€ Permits should be defined to apply only to the â€œRestrictedâ€ category of materials (including the accompanying cautions specified by OMRI), with the continuing exclusion of â€œProhibitedâ€ materials being maintained. 2) Home-owners have plenty of safe alternatives for lawn care (e.g. see http://www.sierraclub.ca/national/programs/health-environment/pesticides/non-toxic-lawn-care.shtml and http://www.sierraclub.ca/national/programs/health-environment/pesticides/index.shtml ). 3) The best regulations will include commercial sprayers in the prohibitions, not leave them out as New Brunswick and PEI have done at this point. When chemicals are banned from retail shelves to protect the public, lawn care companies should not continue using them. Promises of â€œspot sprayingâ€ are no protection. Federal definitions of the size of a â€œspotâ€ for certain products can exceed the size of most residential lawns. If exemptions are to be given for a lawn-care company to apply for the use of stronger pesticides in special circumstances, approved less-toxic pest removal methods must be shown to have been attempted; then documentation submitted that this has failed, and that the pest is a serious problem. There should be adequate time for a ruling on special permission from officials, with the understanding that this is considered a privilege, not a right; and that the sterile, mono-culture lawn is no longer considered a virtue, but instead recognized as a health threat that lowers quality of living and property values. 4) Real estate agents may be concerned that certain buyers would be \'turned off\' if they don\'t see a mono-culture lawn. But government must put health above such superficial concerns, and a pesticide-free neighbourhood ultimately makes a better selling point. 5) Regulations should include all cosmetic landscaping, ie residential trees, shrubs, and flowers. 6) Regulations should also explicitly include all property types: private, public, semi-public, municipal, and commercial properties. 7) Golf courses- pesticide use phase-out should be outlined in the regulations- at the very least: buffer zones for residences bordering on golf courses in the first year, then restrictions, then a ban, as is already in place in Quebec.There should be immediate regulation to establish a no-spray buffer zone around all homes of people with medical environmental illnesses. 8) Canadians need STRONG regulations to protect people, pets and nature from unnecessary toxic cosmetic pesticides. Lawn-care companies and retailers will do better business with organic products, farming would be minimally affected by these regulations, and government enforcement needs should be minimal. The only losers would be corporations who choose to keep selling toxic products for unnecessary applications. If legal action is threatened, it should be ignored. The NAFTA suit brought by Dow Chemical against the government of Canada is over Quebec\'s ban of 2,4-D, and should have no effect on B.C.\'s regulation choices. The Supreme Court of Canada decision on a previous legal challenge in 2005 confirmed the right of governments to act proactively to minimize potential health risks. 9) Every year health care costs are taking a bigger piece out of Canadian government budgets. Strong pesticide regulatory policy will lo','2011-11-27T17:10:24+0000',0,208355,'2014-10-29 13:23:22'),('198826403502374_129175653859205','dddae424503633477c35cfffc0c80adff57fdf76','Action Alert on Pesticides! The B.C. gov_t is conducting an online survey to gauge citizensâ€™ views on a proposed ban on the use of cosmetic pesticides. It only takes a few minutes to fill out the questionnaire. The deadline for submissions is Friday_ December 16_ 2011. We urge everyone_ no matter where you live_ to please register your support! http://tinyurl.com/3gxkruf ','2011-11-24T19:51:27+0000','129175653859205_209534','e66a4983ca74d41961b2ef1b51084a2ad64518a2',0,'con\'t\'d [feel free to copy] **Here is some extra information from notes by Helen Jones MSc., Hon. Zool (UBC), Ed.D. (Col. Univ.) , E-mail: hjones@chebucto.ns.ca Past Member: Pesticide Bylaw Advisory Committee for Halifax Regional Municipality , Board Member, Real Alternatives to Toxins in the Environment (RATE) Past Member and Supporter, Pesticide Free Nova Scotia (PFNS- documents: http://www.ecologyaction.ca/content/publications-0#pesticides ) * â€œCGSB refers to the Canadian General Standards Boardâ€™s Organic Standard, and OMRI refers to Organic Materials Review Institute in Eugene, Oregon, one of two world bodies that provide technical information on generic and brand name materials for organic certification bodies in North America. The OMRI and CGSB lists are updated automatically and frequently, and are supervised by highly qualified advisory bodies. These organizations give approval only to materials and products for which the manufacturer has fully disclosed all ingredients (listed and unlisted), and which have been determined by their technical advisors to contain nothing harmful. To take advantage of this approach when drafting regulations, simply specify that if a product or material is prohibited by the organic standard of the Canadian General Standards Board and/or by the Organic Materials Review Institute then it is also prohibited by the BC provincial-wide pesticide code, e.g., synthetic pesticides, including insecticides, fungicides, and herbicides, as well as any product in which they are present whether or not the product has been given a Pest Control Product Number (PCP#) in Canada, and organic and other natural materials (e.g., nicotine and rotenone) prohibited by the organic standard of Canadian General Standards Board (CGSB) and/or by the Organic Materials Review Institute (OMRI). This can also make it possible to not get caught with being forced to accept certain â€œnatural materialsâ€ that are dangerous to human health (for example, pyrethrums, which can cause fatal allergic reactions). Also worth considering is the inclusion of the words â€œmetaboliteâ€™ and â€œdegradation productâ€ as part of the prohibition. See the Province of New Brunswick, in its Pesticides Control Act (Chapter P-8), which defines â€œpesticideâ€ in part as: â€œ .. any metabolite or degradation product of such product, device, organism, substance or thing â€¦â€. The metabolites and breakdown products of pesticides can be as toxic or much more toxic that the named pesticide itself, yet they are frequently unregulated, untracked and unmonitored because they exist outside the definition and therefore outside the law. The adoption of these approaches are well worth consideration if the protection of public health is given an appropriately high priority. Accessing Information on Products and Generic Materials Standards for Organic Agriculture Look at http://www.tpsgc-pwgsc.gc.ca/ongc-cgsb/publications/nouvelles-news/calibre/014-002/art05-eng.html \"FAQs on the Organic Production Systems Standards ..... Including #14, What substances are permitted and prohibited for use in organic agriculture? CAN/CGSB-32.311, Organic Production Systems Â­ Permitted Substances Lists, includes the following substances lists: Ã¯â€šÂ§ Crop production including fertilizers, plant foods, soil amendments, crop production aids and materials, and weed management Ã¯â€šÂ§ Livestock production including feed, feed additives and feed supplements, health care products and production aids Ã¯â€šÂ§ Processing and sanitation including organic ingredients, non-organic ingredients and with organic ingredients, processing aids, cleaners, disinfectants and sanitizers, and pest control substances. The application and use of these substances must be in accordance with the requirements outlined in CAN/CGSB-32.310, Organic Production Systems - General Principles an