 flu shot. Three years ago I was diagnosed with a rare_ fast-growing type of breast cancer called triple negative. Iâ€™m very lucky to be alive. And extremely grateful for the exceptional care I received at the Norris Cotton Cancer Center.    Before I started chemotherapy treatment_ my oncologist told me that my family and I should get a flu shot. He explained that my immune system would be compromised because of the chemo drugs_ and that my close family and friends should try very hard not to expose me to the flu virus. He said: â€œYou have a hard road ahead of you. The last thing we want is for your treatment to be derailed by something like the flu.â€    He was right. It was a hard road. Going through treatment was the single most humiliating_ demoralizing and dehumanizing experience of my life. I wouldnâ€™t wish it on my worst enemy. There were days I was so sick I couldnâ€™t lift my head off of my pillow. But as hard as the treatment was_ it saved my life. Again_ Iâ€™m very lucky. Thatâ€™s why the notion of getting the flu on top of having cancer is inconceivable to me.     Getting the flu shot is an act of kindness to those fighting for their lives. For more information about getting a flu shot_ visit http://patients.dartmouth-hitchcock.org/health_information/flu_vaccine_information.html.    -Victoria','https://scontent-a.xx.fbcdn.net/hphotos-xap1/v/t1.0-9/s130x130/1376565_10153268442550462_66034349_n.jpg?oh=243aac4a2e64fd619fe0907e0bb54a95&oe=54B21A15','https://www.facebook.com/dartmouthcancer/photos/a.10150269922540462.502490.10150117443575462/10153268442550462/?type=1&relevant_count=1','facebook.com','2013-10-03T14:05:55+0000',1380809155,17,18,1,1,0,1,2,21,'10150117443575462_10153268442670462','https://www.facebook.com/10150117443575462/posts/10153268442670462','Norris Cotton Cancer Center',24648,'2014-10-29 12:07:16',1),('status','post_user_10150117443575462','Wear purple and WIN three personal training sessions with the trainer of your choice during the 