om/10150117443575462/posts/10153067037305462','Norris Cotton Cancer Center',24672,'2014-10-29 12:07:16',1),('link','post_page_10150117443575462','Is lung cancer screening on its way to being routinely offered in an annual physical like a mammogram? Not for everyone. Learn more about what last week_s opinion by the USPSTF means. http://cancer.dartmouth.edu/focus/lung_cancer_CT_scan.html','https://fbexternal-a.akamaihd.net/safe_image.php?d=AQAKj9nAvr3Nm7KD&w=158&h=158&url=https%3A%2F%2Ffbcdn-sphotos-a-a.akamaihd.net%2Fhphotos-ak-ash3%2Fq71%2Fs720x720%2F1119942_10153063889805462_1602820240_o.jpg','http://cancer.dartmouth.edu/focus/lung_cancer_CT_scan.html','cancer.dartmouth.edu','2013-08-06T21:47:45+0000',1375825665,4,4,1,1,0,0,1,6,'10150117443575462_10153063890635462','https://www.facebook.com/10150117443575462/posts/10153063890635462','Norris Cotton Cancer Center',24673,'2014-10-29 12:07:16',1),('photo','post_page_10150117443575462','One of the most rewarding parts of my job is writing Focus stories about the amazing people who are part of the NCCC community. These inspiring people always make me remember just how important the work here is.    At The Prouty I get to meet folks Iâ€™ve interviewed by phone during the year. This year the PSNH Power Pushers â€œTeam Vinnieâ€ gathered for a group shot after completing the event (Honoring Cancer_s many Faces. And Fighting Back http://cancer.dartmouth.edu/focus/prouty-psnh-vinnie.html). Later in the day I met up with Amy and baby Briar Grappone with other members of the amazing â€œTeam Gregâ€ (Do Something to Help Fight Cancer http://cancer.dartmouth.edu/focus/do_something_fight_cancer.html). RD','https://scontent-a.xx.fbcdn.net/hphotos-frc3/v/t1.0-9/s130x130/644223_10153047889765462_253587679_n.jpg?oh=d7cc3085b909670afa91e1300c8ad235&oe=54AC11F6','https://www.facebook.com/dartmouthcancer/photos/a.10150269922540462.502490.10150117443575462/10153047889765462/?type=1&relevant_count=1','facebook.com','2013-08-04T11:20:00+0000',1375615200,3,3,0,0,0,0,0,3,'10150117443575462_10153053451010462','https://www.facebook.com/10150117443575462/posts/10153053451010462','Norris Cotton Cancer Center',24674,'2014-10-29 12:07:16',1),('status','post_user_10150117443575462','Seven years ago today I was planning my husband_s birthday dinner when the phone rang. It was the doctor who had done the biopsy at DHMC two days before. I knew it wasn_t good news when he asked if I was sitting down. After spending some time crying_ I decided I was done with the negativity and tried to stay positive through the whole thing. I had a mastectomy & reconstruction_ underwent almost 2 years of chemo_ then a total of 5 years of hormone therapy_ a second surgery last year having bilateral mastectomy (which I wish I had done in the first place_ but then again hindsight is always 20/20).   Anyway_ after being _invited_ to participate for the nth time in one of those _awareness_ games that really does nothing to raise awareness or support those going through treatments_ I got to thinking about all of the people who have supported me in the past 7 years. (and I have tears in my eyes as I type this). I am not including names_ but you_ll know who you are. (These are not in any particular order.)  Thank you to my mom for crying with me after that initial phone call.  Thank you to my family for going with me to the consultation appointments to help me decide which course of action I should do.  Thank you to the friend who cleaned my house from top to bottom_ even though she_s convinced this place is haunted.  Thank you to the kindergartners who would give me a pat on the back because _that_s what mom does when I_m feeling sick and it makes me feel better._  Thank you to the family_ friends_ students & co-workers who shaved their heads (or got a really short cut) to show support.  Thank you to the neighbor who gave a bouquet of flowers to Charles at the mailbox _just because_.  Thank you to the cousin who wore pink when he skied in the Race to Beat Cancer.  Thank you to all the coworkers/neighbors/friends/family/ & _school family_ who brought food when I felt too sick to cook.  Thank to the friend who invited me to her house when I was feeling better to _come make a card_ and introduced me to a new hobby!  Thank you to the parent who organized a fundraiser to help pay for the portion of the cost of the prosthetics that the insurance didn_t cover.  Thank you to all the people who keep telling me _It_s what_s on the inside that makes you beautiful._  Thank you to the person who anonymously sends a get well card with $20 tucked inside _to help with expenses._  Thank you to the doctors_ nurses_ and volunteers who were so wonderful to me during my treatments.  Thank you to the coworkers who said _don_t worry_ we_ve got this_ when I felt too sick to go outside for recess duty.  Thank you to the school board who gave me as many sick days as I needed.  Thank you to my brother who asked _Has not having breasts improved your golf swing?_ (because a sense of humor is essential!)  Thank you to the almost-sister-in-law who notices your clothes no longer fit and volunteers to go shopping for you.  Thank you to Two Rivers Ride for Cancer who paid for some oil so I could have my surgery in the winter.   Thank you to the friends who came by to check on the animals when we had to be gone for more than a couple hours.  Thank you to my mother-in-law who mailed me flannel pjs & a soft _lounge suit_ so I could be comfortable during the days I was hanging around the house.  Thank you to my sister-in-law who sent soft hats to keep my bald head warm. And my niece who offered to fly out here to help if I needed it.  Thank you to the friends who sent me cards_ emails_ jokes_ and stories to keep me occupied_ or sympathize_ or _just because I was thinking of you_.  And most of all_ thank you to my husband who was there for every single appointment_ who sat with me while I was being hooked up to an iv_ or having yet another procedure_ who loves me no matter what size my chest is (or isn_t).',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2013-08-01T19:52:28+0000',1375386748,1,1,1,1,0,0,0,2,'10150117443575462_10153043208390462','https://www.facebook.com/10150117443575462/posts/10153043208390462','Norris Cotton Cancer Center',24675,'2014-10-29 12:07:16',1),('status','post_user_10150117443575462','Wanted to mention that I just celebrated 5 YEARS CANCER FREE and couldnt have done it without my AMAZING TEAM at NCCC. So THANK YOU Dr. Eisenberg for getting me through my surgeries_ Dr. Earnstoff for being a fantastic oncologist_ Nancy Crosby for Being the BEST assistant dr. and oncologist (and for holding my hand through some of the harder days)_ The entire team of Oncology Nurses and Staff in the Infusion Center and all the WONDERFUL support staff that help NCCC be the BEST PLACE for cancer care!!  I was told I wouldnt be here today_ and I am celebrating  all of you with helping to get me to this milestone!!!!',NULL,NULL,NULL,'2013-08-01T17:31:32+0000',1375378292,0,0,1,1,0,0,0,1,'10150117443575462_10153042815515462','https://www.facebook.com/10150117443575462/posts/10153042815515462','Norris Cotton Cancer Center',24676,'2014-10-29 12:07:16',1),('photo','post_page_10150117443575462','_Can cat poop cure cancer?_  That_s what I wanted to know. You see I prepared this poster for the  Prouty Page for The Friends of Norris Cotton Cancer Center. A few days later a national story came out about the dangers of T. Gondii in cat poop. But I knew we were using it to kill melanoma tumors. So I contacted the Principal Investigator Steve Fiering to see if it was the same organism.   He answered: _Yes it is the same organism_ Toxoplasma gondii_ but CPS_  the strain we work with_ developed by David Bzik has a deletion of a gene so that it cannot replicate unless it is in a culture dish with a special media.  However it still can stimulate the immune response that causes the tumor to be eliminated.  It is similar in some ways to enginee